Rights as what?

512
00:34:28,365 --> 00:34:30,201
An American?

513
00:34:30,233 --> 00:34:33,371
Rights as what, Counselor?

514
00:34:33,403 --> 00:34:35,206
We are in a battle
for civilization.

515
00:34:35,239 --> 00:34:38,443
This Russian spy came here
to threaten our way of life.

516
00:34:38,476 --> 00:34:40,545
Now, I have a courtroom
of people waiting.

517
00:34:40,577 --> 00:34:42,579
Get out there, sit
beside the Russian.

518
00:34:42,612 --> 00:34:44,748
Let us get this over and done.

519
00:34:44,782 --> 00:34:47,217
And, your motion is denied.

520
00:34:49,719 --> 00:34:52,155
He should take some
insurance out on himself.

521
00:34:52,657 --> 00:34:53,757
How did we do?

522
00:34:53,791 --> 00:34:55,791
In there.

523
00:34:57,661 --> 00:34:59,630
Not too good.

524
00:34:59,664 --> 00:35:01,666
Apparently, you are not
an American citizen.

525
00:35:01,699 --> 00:35:03,634
That is true.

526
00:35:03,668 --> 00:35:05,436
And according to your boss.

527
00:35:05,469 --> 00:35:07,469
You are not a Soviet
citizen either.

528
00:35:08,405 --> 00:35:10,974
Well, the boss is
not always, right.

529
00:35:12,275 --> 00:35:14,275
He is always the boss.

530
00:35:18,715 --> 00:35:20,715
Do you never worry?

531
00:35:20,818 --> 00:35:22,818
Would it help?

532
00:35:29,827 --> 00:35:31,827
All rise!

533
00:35:33,697 --> 00:35:37,434
"I pledge allegiance
to the Flag."

534
00:35:37,467 --> 00:35:40,538
"Of the United
States of America."

535
00:35:40,570 --> 00:35:44,541
"And to the Republic
for which it stands."

536
00:35:44,574 --> 00:35:49,447
"One Nation under
God, indivisible."

537
00:35:49,480 --> 00:35:51,748
"With liberty and
justice for all."

538
00:35:55,786 --> 00:35:57,588
<i>First, you have to
know what happens,</i>

539
00:35:57,621 --> 00:35:59,657
<i>when an atomic bomb explodes.</i>

540
00:36:02,360 --> 00:36:05,496
<i>There is a bright flash,
brighter than the sun.</i>

541
00:36:05,530 --> 00:36:09,666
<i>It can smash buildings,
break windows all over town.</i>

542
00:36:11,735 --> 00:36:14,739
<i>But if you are in shelter
and cover like Bert,</i>

543
00:36:14,771 --> 00:36:16,706
<i>you will be much safer.</i>

544
00:36:16,740 --> 00:36:18,842
<i>There are two kinds of attack,</i>

545
00:36:18,876 --> 00:36:21,311
<i>with warning, without
any warning.</i>

546
00:36:26,384 --> 00:36:27,617
What is going on in here?

547
00:36:27,652 --> 00:36:29,519
<i>Okay, Dad.
This is very important.</i>

548
00:36:29,554 --> 00:36:31,588
When the war begins, the
first thing, they do...

549
00:36:31,621 --> 00:36:34,324
Is cut off all the water,
and, all the electricity.

550
00:36:34,358 --> 00:36:36,460
The first thing we should
do is keep filled,

551
00:36:36,494 --> 00:36:37,827
use the shower in your room,

552
00:36:37,862 --> 00:36:40,364
use the sink downstairs,
the garden hose outside.

553
00:36:40,498 --> 00:36:42,465
Those are good ideas.

554
00:36:42,500 --> 00:36:44,467
Roger, I do not see this.

555
00:36:44,501 --> 00:36:46,501
As being something, you
have to worry.

556
00:36:47,804 --> 00:36:49,072
Yeah, but when you
hear the sirens.

557
00:36:49,206 --> 00:36:52,309
There may not be enough time
to fill the tub and the sinks.

558
00:36:53,344 --> 00:36:55,344
Not will have any sirens.

559
00:36:56,414 --> 00:36:57,748
What is this?

560
00:36:57,782 --> 00:36:58,815
When the bomb comes,

561
00:36:58,849 --> 00:37:01,686
the Reds will aim go for
the Empire State Building.

562
00:37:01,719 --> 00:37:04,521
But, the bomb goes off
at 10,000 feet up.

563
00:37:04,554 --> 00:37:06,489
In Life magazine, it
is called an air burst.

564
00:37:06,523 --> 00:37:08,525
And, if the bomb
is 50 megatons.

565
00:37:08,559 --> 00:37:11,728
The blast wave goes
out and out and out.

566
00:37:11,762 --> 00:37:14,297
And, melts everything
from here to here.

567
00:37:14,331 --> 00:37:16,331
Including where we live.

568
00:37:16,833 --> 00:37:18,501
Yeah. Right there.

569
00:37:18,536 --> 00:37:19,637
You know Roger,

570
00:37:19,670 --> 00:37:22,306
no one is dropping
Atomic bombs on us.

571
00:37:22,340 --> 00:37:23,708
The Russians want to.

572
00:37:23,740 --> 00:37:25,740
You know that Russian
person, you are defending.

573
00:37:25,876 --> 00:37:26,643
He is here to get
things ready.

574
00:37:26,976 --> 00:37:28,579
For the people who
drop the bombs.

575
00:37:28,612 --> 00:37:30,681
No. No, he is not...
Not is here for that.

576
00:37:30,715 --> 00:37:32,315
He is not even Russian.

577
00:37:32,349 --> 00:37:34,385
He was born, we think,
in Northern England.

578
00:37:34,418 --> 00:37:36,418
Yeah. But, he is a
spy for Russia.

579
00:37:36,920 --> 00:37:38,922
I do not even understand.
What are you doing?

580
00:37:38,956 --> 00:37:41,391
You are not a Communist.
So, why are you defending one?

581
00:37:41,425 --> 00:37:43,393
Well, because it is my job.

582
00:37:43,427 --> 00:37:45,463
It never used to be.

583
00:38:14,992 --> 00:38:17,427
<i>In the case of the United
States of America,</i>

584
00:38:17,460 --> 00:38:19,664
versus Rudolf Abel.

585
00:38:19,697 --> 00:38:22,365
As to the first count
in the indictment.

586
00:38:22,400 --> 00:38:24,467
<I>How do you find the defendant?</I>

587
00:38:24,501 --> 00:38:26,737
<I>Guilty or not guilty?</I>

588
00:38:26,771 --> 00:38:28,771
Guilty.

589
00:38:29,407 --> 00:38:30,641
<I>As to the second count?</I>

590
00:38:30,974 --> 00:38:31,876
Guilty.

591
00:38:32,909 --> 00:38:34,978
<I>As to the third count?</I>

592
00:38:35,012 --> 00:38:36,246
Guilty.

593
00:38:36,280 --> 00:38:38,648
Your honor. I make a motion to
set aside these guilty verdicts.

594
00:38:38,682 --> 00:38:40,418
Against the weight
of evidence.

595
00:38:40,451 --> 00:38:41,952
Denied.

596
00:38:41,985 --> 00:38:43,853
The jury discharged.

597
00:38:43,887 --> 00:38:45,887
Thank you.

598
00:38:45,956 --> 00:38:47,557
I would like to add that,
if I were one of you.

599
00:38:47,891 --> 00:38:49,891
I would have reached
the same verdict.

600
00:38:51,494 --> 00:38:53,963
Sentencing will be.

601
00:38:55,599 --> 00:38:57,599
<i>November 15.</i>

602
00:39:05,943 --> 00:39:08,512
The death sentence is not
a foregone conclusion.

603
00:39:08,545 --> 00:39:10,545
Do not worry.

604
00:39:10,681 --> 00:39:12,849
I am not afraid to die,
Mr. Donovan.

605
00:39:15,820 --> 00:39:17,722
Although.

606
00:39:17,755 --> 00:39:19,755
It would not be
my first choice.

607
00:39:23,760 --> 00:39:25,996
You left this behind.

608
00:39:27,664 --> 00:39:29,664
Thank you.

609
00:39:31,534 --> 00:39:33,534
Thank you very much!

610
00:39:53,056 --> 00:39:55,693
You have never asked me,
if the charges were true.

611
00:39:58,496 --> 00:40:01,431
If I am indeed a spy.

612
00:40:03,567 --> 00:40:05,068
This is how we do it.

613
00:40:05,101 --> 00:40:07,503
The case against you matters.

614
00:40:07,505 --> 00:40:08,873
Making them prove it matters.

615
00:40:08,905 --> 00:40:10,807
The fiction is...

616
00:40:10,840 --> 00:40:12,809
Whether you did it or
not does not matter.

617
00:40:12,842 --> 00:40:15,813
The state has to prove
it, that you are a spy.

618
00:40:15,846 --> 00:40:17,846
You are not curious.

619
00:40:17,981 --> 00:40:19,550
No, not really.

620
00:40:19,583 --> 00:40:22,085
I always assumed you
were an artist.

621
00:40:22,119 --> 00:40:24,054
<I>My wife, she is the artist.</I>

622
00:40:24,088 --> 00:40:26,690
She is a musician.

623
00:40:26,724 --> 00:40:30,527
In the Children's
Orchestra of Moscow.

624
00:40:30,561 --> 00:40:31,896
What instrument?

625
00:40:31,929 --> 00:40:33,929
The Harp.

626
00:40:35,865 --> 00:40:37,865
Then, she is an Angel.

627
00:40:47,878 --> 00:40:50,614
Standing there like that,
you remind me a man,.

628
00:40:50,648 --> 00:40:52,882
Who used to come to our house.
When I was young.

629
00:40:54,150 --> 00:40:57,655
My father used to say:
"Watch this man."

630
00:40:58,822 --> 00:41:02,092
I did every time he came.

631
00:41:02,126 --> 00:41:05,094
And, never once.

632
00:41:05,128 --> 00:41:07,965
He did anything remarkable.

633
00:41:10,166 --> 00:41:12,536
And, I remind you of him.

634
00:41:15,873 --> 00:41:19,777
This one time, I was about
the age of your son.

635
00:41:19,809 --> 00:41:22,913
Our house overrun by
partisan border guards.

636
00:41:26,717 --> 00:41:29,018
Dozens of them.

637
00:41:29,052 --> 00:41:31,088
My father was beaten and
my mother was beaten.

638
00:41:31,121 --> 00:41:34,525
This man, my father's
friend, he was beaten.

639
00:41:36,193 --> 00:41:38,193
I watched this man.

640
00:41:41,632 --> 00:41:43,632
Every time they hit him.

641
00:41:45,135 --> 00:41:47,135
He stood back up again.

642
00:41:49,039 --> 00:41:51,039
They hit him harder.

643
00:41:52,876 --> 00:41:54,945
Still, he gets back on his feet.

644
00:41:58,648 --> 00:42:00,885
I think because of this,
they stopped beating him.

645
00:42:00,918 --> 00:42:02,918
They let him alive.

646
00:42:10,827 --> 00:42:12,862
I remember them saying it.

647
00:42:20,704 --> 00:42:22,773
It means like:

648
00:42:25,108 --> 00:42:27,108
"Standing man."

649
00:42:30,213 --> 00:42:32,213
"Standing man."

650
00:42:43,092 --> 00:42:45,695
- Hello, Jim!
- Millie, you are a vision.

651
00:42:45,728 --> 00:42:48,097
Mortie is busy getting ready.

652
00:42:48,132 --> 00:42:50,132
Come on in.

653
00:42:51,135 --> 00:42:53,804
- Scotch, Jim?
- Yes, please. Thank you.

654
00:42:53,836 --> 00:42:55,836
Just a drop of water.

655
00:42:56,673 --> 00:42:57,942
Your honor.

656
00:42:57,974 --> 00:43:00,844
Hello, Jim! Just going out.

657
00:43:00,878 --> 00:43:02,846
I got a few minutes though.

658
00:43:02,880 --> 00:43:05,849
March of Dimes thing.
Millie is active.

659
00:43:07,284 --> 00:43:09,052
Well, thank you for seeing me.

660
00:43:09,085 --> 00:43:13,123
I just wanted to give you my
two cents on the sentencing.

661
00:43:13,157 --> 00:43:16,260
And, I thought maybe, I
should pester you at home.

662
00:43:16,293 --> 00:43:19,262
As not all of my points
are narrowly legal.

663
00:43:19,295 --> 00:43:22,065
Yeah. It is that kind of case.

664
00:43:22,099 --> 00:43:24,134
I hope I was not too
scratchy during the trial.

665
00:43:24,168 --> 00:43:27,003
It is exactly what you say.

666
00:43:27,036 --> 00:43:29,036
Nothing about this
is narrowly legal.

667
00:43:30,773 --> 00:43:32,773
There are bigger issues.

668
00:43:33,309 --> 00:43:35,309
Bigger issues!

669
00:43:37,313 --> 00:43:39,313
Thank you, thank you.

670
00:43:42,119 --> 00:43:43,887
Sir?

671
00:43:43,920 --> 00:43:45,922
I think it could
be considered.

672
00:43:45,956 --> 00:43:48,726
In the best interests
of the United States.

673
00:43:48,759 --> 00:43:51,695
That Abel remains alive.

674
00:43:52,195 --> 00:43:53,998
Why?

675
00:43:54,030 --> 00:43:55,766
I am not saying, I
made up my mind.

676
00:43:55,798 --> 00:43:56,934
But if he was going
to cooperate,

677
00:43:56,967 --> 00:43:59,166
work with the government.
He would have done it already.

678
00:43:59,369 --> 00:44:00,269
- True, but the issue here.
- You cannot.

679
00:44:00,304 --> 00:44:02,304
Excuse me.

680
00:44:06,809 --> 00:44:09,713
You cannot say it is in the best
interest of the United States.

681
00:44:09,996 --> 00:44:13,916
That he spend the rest of
his days in a prison cell.

682
00:44:13,951 --> 00:44:16,019
How is this national interest?

683
00:44:16,052 --> 00:44:18,387
Not the incarceration
itself, Sir.

684
00:44:19,856 --> 00:44:22,925
It is possible in
the near future.

685
00:44:22,960 --> 00:44:25,195
An American of
equivalent rank.

686
00:44:25,228 --> 00:44:27,965
Might be captured
by Soviet Russia.

687
00:44:27,998 --> 00:44:30,233
We might want to have
someone to trade.

688
00:44:30,266 --> 00:44:31,635
Wow!

689
00:44:31,969 --> 00:44:34,137
That sounds like what-ifs.

690
00:44:34,170 --> 00:44:36,170
You could do that until
the cows come home.

691
00:44:36,206 --> 00:44:39,043
It is my business, what-ifs.
I am in insurance.

692
00:44:39,175 --> 00:44:41,344
And, there is nothing
implausible about this one.

693
00:44:41,378 --> 00:44:44,782
It is entirely really,
of what could happen.

694
00:44:44,815 --> 00:44:48,184
It is the kind of probability
for people buys insurance.

695
00:44:48,217 --> 00:44:52,155
If we send this person to his death.
We leave ourselves wide open.

696
00:44:52,188 --> 00:44:54,958
No policy in our back pocket,

697
00:44:54,992 --> 00:44:56,992
for the day the storm comes.

698
00:44:58,996 --> 00:45:01,231
Nice speech.

699
00:45:01,264 --> 00:45:06,903
Sir, there is also the
humanitarian an argument.

700
00:45:06,936 --> 00:45:10,007
Should he die for doing the
job they sent him to do?

701
00:45:12,141 --> 00:45:14,141
All right! Counselor.

702
00:45:16,012 --> 00:45:18,012
I have to run.

703
00:45:20,983 --> 00:45:22,983
Good see you, Jim.

704
00:45:26,356 --> 00:45:28,356
I will walk you out.

705
00:45:31,295 --> 00:45:33,295
<i>All rise!</i>

706
00:45:34,030 --> 00:45:35,231
<i>The United States
District Court.</i>

707
00:45:35,465 --> 00:45:38,034
<i>For the Eastern District of
New York is now in session.</i>

708
00:45:38,068 --> 00:45:40,137
<i>The honorable Mortimer
Byers presiding.</i>

709
00:45:44,842 --> 00:45:46,842
<i>Be seated.</i>

710
00:45:58,088 --> 00:46:00,088
The defendant
will please rise.

711
00:46:14,438 --> 00:46:16,172
In the measured
judgment of this court,

712
00:46:16,206 --> 00:46:17,440
the following sentence,

713
00:46:17,474 --> 00:46:19,976
based upon the jury's
verdict of guilty.

714
00:46:20,010 --> 00:46:22,311
As to each count
of the indictment,

715
00:46:22,346 --> 00:46:27,150
<I>is believe to meet the
test, which has stated.</I>

716
00:46:27,184 --> 00:46:30,086
Pursuant to the verdict of
guilty as to all counts.

717
00:46:32,422 --> 00:46:34,324
The defendant is committed
to the custody,

718
00:46:34,358 --> 00:46:36,425
of the Attorney General
of the United States.

719
00:46:38,461 --> 00:46:40,963
For imprisonment in a
federal institution,

720
00:46:40,998 --> 00:46:44,434
to be selected by him for
a period of 30 years.

721
00:46:45,568 --> 00:46:47,938
<I>Marshals, you may take the
defendant into custody.</I>

722
00:46:47,971 --> 00:46:49,072
No... No electrocution?

723
00:46:49,106 --> 00:46:50,074
No. No, no.

724
00:46:50,106 --> 00:46:52,141
Why are not we hanging him?

725
00:46:52,275 --> 00:46:54,577
<I>In the name of God.
Why are not we hanging him?</I>

726
00:46:54,690 --> 00:46:55,411
Sit down!

727
00:46:55,644 --> 00:46:59,148
<I>He is a spy! He is killing
us with his lies!</I>

728
00:46:59,182 --> 00:47:00,918
In the name of God.
Why are not we hanging him?

729
00:47:00,951 --> 00:47:02,951
That is right!

730
00:47:03,519 --> 00:47:05,519
<I>He is a spy!</I>

731
00:47:09,458 --> 00:47:11,360
<I>Mr. Donovan? Mr. Donovan?</I>

732
00:47:11,394 --> 00:47:14,364
- Just one question.
- Just one question, Sir.

733
00:47:21,405 --> 00:47:23,405
My hat! My hat!

734
00:47:25,275 --> 00:47:26,744
Nobody here has a comment.

735
00:47:26,976 --> 00:47:28,512
Mr. and Mrs. Donovan
are not answering questions.

736
00:47:28,644 --> 00:47:29,746
How do you feel now?

737
00:47:29,980 --> 00:47:31,148
This national
nightmare is over.

738
00:47:31,181 --> 00:47:32,481
Mr. Donovan, are you
happy with the verdict?

739
00:47:32,516 --> 00:47:36,119
We are... We are firm
in case on appeal.

740
00:47:36,152 --> 00:47:38,152
- Appeal?
- Appeal, yes.

741
00:47:51,568 --> 00:47:53,402
<i>Jim, you did a great job.</i>

742
00:47:53,436 --> 00:47:56,206
<i>You fulfilled your
mandate and, then some.</i>

743
00:47:56,239 --> 00:47:58,242
The man is a spy.

744
00:47:58,275 --> 00:48:00,978
The verdict is correct and there
is no reason to appeal it?

745
00:48:01,010 --> 00:48:02,945
There is ample
procedural reason.

746
00:48:02,980 --> 00:48:04,047
We know the search is tainted.

747
00:48:04,081 --> 00:48:05,248
Fourth Amendment issues.

748
00:48:05,282 --> 00:48:07,284
Will always weigh more heavily
in an appellate forum.

749
00:48:07,317 --> 00:48:09,018
We have a good shot.

750
00:48:09,052 --> 00:48:12,021
What about the goddamn
are you talking?

751
00:48:12,054 --> 00:48:15,259
We were supposed to show he had a
capable defense, which we did.

752
00:48:15,291 --> 00:48:17,360
Why are you citing the
goddamn constitution at me?

753
00:48:17,594 --> 00:48:19,295
Tom, if you look
me in the eye.

754
00:48:19,329 --> 00:48:21,364
And, tell me we do
not have grounds,

755
00:48:21,398 --> 00:48:22,398
for an appeal, I will
drop it right now.

756
00:48:22,431 --> 00:48:24,568
I am not saying that, you
know what I am saying.

757
00:48:24,601 --> 00:48:27,036
Tom is saying there is
a cost to these things.

758
00:48:27,070 --> 00:48:28,572
That is right.

759
00:48:28,605 --> 00:48:31,240
A cost to both your
family and your firm.

760
00:49:06,242 --> 00:49:09,079
I missed music.

761
00:49:09,112 --> 00:49:11,447
They checked the radio to make sure
there was no transmitter in it.

762
00:49:11,481 --> 00:49:13,481
I am sure they did.

763
00:49:19,489 --> 00:49:22,092
That is a very great
artist, Shostakovitch.

764
00:49:37,574 --> 00:49:39,574
I think.

765
00:49:40,543 --> 00:49:44,514
Our strongest grounds
for reversal,

766
00:49:44,547 --> 00:49:46,547
are constitutional.

