Fine. Fine.

1014
01:06:38,626 --> 01:06:41,197
Best this all remains
confidential.

1015
01:06:41,230 --> 01:06:46,302
Let us not discuss any of this
with Mary or anyone else.

1016
01:06:46,335 --> 01:06:48,471
Share the correspondence
only with us.

1017
01:06:48,503 --> 01:06:50,338
Let us know what they
want to do and when.

1018
01:06:50,373 --> 01:06:53,309
I have no client, no
wife and no country.

1019
01:06:53,342 --> 01:06:56,411
Do not know what for I
am doing or when or who?

1020
01:06:56,445 --> 01:06:58,179
You are doing it
for your country.

1021
01:06:58,213 --> 01:07:00,215
But, your country does
not know that yet.

1022
01:07:00,248 --> 01:07:03,351
What about my client, the other
person in this equation? My person?

1023
01:07:03,385 --> 01:07:05,253
Your person? You
mean the Russian.

1024
01:07:05,286 --> 01:07:07,155
He is not your person
anymore, Counselor.

1025
01:07:07,188 --> 01:07:10,226
Your person is Francis
Gary Powers now.

1026
01:07:10,259 --> 01:07:13,128
What do I tell to Rudolf Abel?

1027
01:07:13,161 --> 01:07:15,161
Tell him not to drop dead.

1028
01:09:07,510 --> 01:09:09,510
Professor?

1029
01:09:14,882 --> 01:09:15,984
Professor?

1030
01:09:16,484 --> 01:09:18,453
Papa went to university.

1031
01:09:18,487 --> 01:09:20,655
You should not be
here, Frederic.

1032
01:09:20,689 --> 01:09:22,557
They are having classes today.

1033
01:09:22,591 --> 01:09:24,827
He went to see where he goes.

1034
01:09:24,859 --> 01:09:26,427
What are you doing here?

1035
01:09:26,462 --> 01:09:28,463
I came to get you,
and your father.

1036
01:09:28,497 --> 01:09:30,498
You have to come with me. You
might not get out tomorrow.

1037
01:09:30,533 --> 01:09:31,734
Just... Just leave.

1038
01:09:31,766 --> 01:09:34,203
Yes. Yes, yes, yes, leave.
Right now.

1039
01:10:05,367 --> 01:10:07,735
Go back. Go back.

1040
01:10:07,770 --> 01:10:10,305
I will be okay. I am American.
Go back.

1041
01:10:10,338 --> 01:10:12,574
Go back to your father.
We will find another way. Go.

1042
01:10:18,413 --> 01:10:19,414
Hey.

1043
01:10:19,782 --> 01:10:21,782
Sir. Hi.

1044
01:10:24,653 --> 01:10:26,488
Papers, please.

1045
01:10:26,521 --> 01:10:28,623
The Student Frederic Pryor.

1046
01:10:28,657 --> 01:10:30,826
Yes, student.

1047
01:10:35,157 --> 01:10:37,157
What kind of photos?

1048
01:10:41,804 --> 01:10:44,340
My name is Frederic Pryor.
I am an economics student.

1049
01:10:46,442 --> 01:10:50,511
It is my dissertation.
My thesis.

1050
01:10:52,614 --> 01:10:54,082
You see. Look, look.

1051
01:10:54,115 --> 01:10:57,720
"The foreign trade system of the
European Communist nations."

1052
01:11:02,890 --> 01:11:04,890
It was a lot of work.

1053
01:11:11,833 --> 01:11:14,536
No. That is my only copy.

1054
01:11:15,904 --> 01:11:17,904
No!

1055
01:11:19,774 --> 01:11:21,377
<i>Tell me something.</i>

1056
01:11:21,409 --> 01:11:23,479
It came up at the last minute.

1057
01:11:23,511 --> 01:11:25,814
They have offices in London.

1058
01:11:25,847 --> 01:11:28,817
These clients. Not my idea.

1059
01:11:28,850 --> 01:11:31,487
Scotland, this
fishing expedition.

1060
01:11:31,520 --> 01:11:33,721
What kind of
fishing trip, Jim?

1061
01:11:33,756 --> 01:11:36,492
Salmon fishing.

1062
01:11:36,524 --> 01:11:38,564
Just tell me that you are
not going to be in any danger.

1063
01:11:38,594 --> 01:11:39,927
This is just a routine
business trip.

1064
01:11:39,962 --> 01:11:41,962
I will not worry.

1065
01:11:42,398 --> 01:11:44,398
I need my passport.

1066
01:11:48,804 --> 01:11:50,471
Just give me something
to hold on.

1067
01:11:50,506 --> 01:11:52,506
I do not even care
if it is the truth.

1068
01:11:53,942 --> 01:11:55,942
I am doing this for us.

1069
01:12:19,033 --> 01:12:21,002
<I>Mr. Michener here is
your Berlin escort.</I>

1070
01:12:21,036 --> 01:12:23,838
He is an attache with the U.S.
embassy.

1071
01:12:23,872 --> 01:12:26,475
It has gotten goddamn
complicated.

1072
01:12:26,507 --> 01:12:27,876
As you know, the last
letter from Mrs. Abel.

1073
01:12:27,909 --> 01:12:30,011
Whoever she is, talks about
a lawyer in East Berlin.

1074
01:12:30,045 --> 01:12:32,514
Mr. Vogel, whoever he is,
representing her interests, she says.

1075
01:12:32,547 --> 01:12:33,916
Yeah. Vogel says.

1076
01:12:33,948 --> 01:12:35,850
He has gone to the Russian
embassy in East Berlin.

1077
01:12:35,884 --> 01:12:38,520
They may be ready to
trade Abel for Powers.

1078
01:12:38,554 --> 01:12:40,456
No one knows who is who.

1079
01:12:40,488 --> 01:12:41,724
Essentially, they
are Russian, right.

1080
01:12:41,756 --> 01:12:44,560
Well! Soviet. We think so.

1081
01:12:44,592 --> 01:12:47,761
What do you mean? Could we
turn up the heat in here?

1082
01:12:48,630 --> 01:12:50,998
There is a wrinkle.

1083
01:12:51,033 --> 01:12:53,469
They might try to throw
you a curve ball.

1084
01:12:53,502 --> 01:12:56,471
Try to get you to accept another
prisoner other than Powers.

1085
01:12:56,505 --> 01:12:57,840
Another American?

1086
01:12:57,872 --> 01:13:01,009
The East German Stasis picked
up an American student.

1087
01:13:01,042 --> 01:13:02,243
Frederic Pryor.

1088
01:13:02,277 --> 01:13:04,846
The kid they found on the
wrong side of the Wall.

1089
01:13:04,880 --> 01:13:06,648
He is a graduate
student of Yale.

1090
01:13:06,681 --> 01:13:08,716
Came over here to
study economics.

1091
01:13:08,751 --> 01:13:12,587
They are making noises about
trying this kid for espionage.

1092
01:13:12,621 --> 01:13:15,056
Grave offense, capital crime.

1093
01:13:15,090 --> 01:13:19,828
Vogel got in touch with us,
said he represents Pryor.

1094
01:13:19,862 --> 01:13:24,800
Wait a minute! Vogel represents
Mrs. Abel and this kid?

1095
01:13:24,832 --> 01:13:26,832
Yeah, he is busy.

1096
01:13:27,636 --> 01:13:28,703
What is he?

1097
01:13:28,737 --> 01:13:31,073
Vogel is East German or Russian?

1098
01:13:31,105 --> 01:13:33,775
Try to figure it out
when you meet him.

1099
01:13:33,809 --> 01:13:36,078
At Russian embassy, East
Berlin, noon tomorrow.

1100
01:13:36,110 --> 01:13:38,814
Hoffman will show you
how to get there.

1101
01:13:38,846 --> 01:13:40,916
Wait! Show me how to get there.
I am going to have an escort.

1102
01:13:40,948 --> 01:13:42,784
Right?

1103
01:13:42,818 --> 01:13:44,920
That was the plan but as I
said, there is a wrinkle.

1104
01:13:44,953 --> 01:13:47,689
I will not be taking you.
Decision has made.

1105
01:13:47,722 --> 01:13:50,492
No U.S. government personnel are to
cross the border until further notice.

1106
01:13:50,525 --> 01:13:51,726
- Why?
- It is too dangerous.

1107
01:13:51,859 --> 01:13:53,694
<I>The East Germans
grabbed this kid.</I>

1108
01:13:53,729 --> 01:13:57,666
<i>There is a degree of impunity.
We had not anticipated.</i>

1109
01:13:57,698 --> 01:14:00,668
The point is the East German
agenda and the Russian agenda.

1110
01:14:00,702 --> 01:14:02,104
May not be the same thing.

1111
01:14:02,136 --> 01:14:04,006
Try to figure it out
and, act accordingly.

1112
01:14:04,038 --> 01:14:05,841
Try to make a deal.
Powers for Abel.

1113
01:14:05,873 --> 01:14:08,777
What about this
college kid, Pryor?

1114
01:14:09,810 --> 01:14:10,993
Do not you fall for that?

1115
01:14:11,646 --> 01:14:12,713
We can get him out
another time.

1116
01:14:12,747 --> 01:14:14,747
Powers is the whole ball game.

1117
01:14:37,005 --> 01:14:39,005
Where is your room?

1118
01:14:39,707 --> 01:14:41,707
I will be staying
at the Hilton.

1119
01:14:43,110 --> 01:14:45,110
It is not far.

1120
01:14:46,180 --> 01:14:48,750
This is a number
here in West Berlin.

1121
01:14:48,783 --> 01:14:50,783
Memorize it, and
give it back to me.

1122
01:14:51,787 --> 01:14:53,787
No, no. I... I mean, now.

1123
01:14:55,756 --> 01:14:57,759
The Soviets keep cutting
the international lines.

1124
01:14:57,792 --> 01:15:00,028
Local calls are okay.

1125
01:15:00,061 --> 01:15:02,061
Someone will pick
up day and night.

1126
01:15:10,738 --> 01:15:14,076
Now, this docket attached to your
passport will serve as your ticket.

1127
01:15:14,109 --> 01:15:16,109
Into and out of the
Eastern Soviet sector.

1128
01:15:18,113 --> 01:15:20,113
The meeting with Vogel is
set for noon tomorrow.

1129
01:15:26,755 --> 01:15:28,657
There are only a few
routes left to the East.

1130
01:15:28,689 --> 01:15:30,893
You take the S-Bah, the station.
We showed you on the way in.

1131
01:15:30,926 --> 01:15:33,194
You are going to get off at the
Friedrichstrasse station here.

1132
01:15:33,228 --> 01:15:36,131
Walk to the Soviet embassy
on Under den Linden here.

1133
01:15:36,163 --> 01:15:38,800
Look at the map now. You
should not take it with you.

1134
01:15:38,833 --> 01:15:40,935
You are looking at a map. You
are an American. You are a spy.

1135
01:15:40,969 --> 01:15:42,970
You could well detain.

1136
01:15:43,005 --> 01:15:45,073
Just avoid interacting
with people generally.

1137
01:15:45,106 --> 01:15:48,042
You do not... You do not
belong, so do not stick out.

1138
01:15:48,076 --> 01:15:50,177
Food is scarce over there and
things have started to fall apart.

1139
01:15:50,212 --> 01:15:51,412
There are gangs.

1140
01:15:51,445 --> 01:15:54,716
And, rule of law is less firm
established over there.

1141
01:15:54,750 --> 01:15:56,752
Definitely stay
away from the Wall.

1142
01:15:56,784 --> 01:15:57,953
On their side,
there is a line.

1143
01:15:57,985 --> 01:15:59,020
Cleared of buildings
along the Wall.

1144
01:15:59,054 --> 01:16:00,756
They call it the "Death Line."

1145
01:16:00,788 --> 01:16:02,690
Cross it and you will shot.

1146
01:16:02,724 --> 01:16:05,060
Where is there any outcome here?
I am not either detained or shot.

1147
01:16:05,092 --> 01:16:07,695
You do not worry too much,
about what Michener said.

1148
01:16:07,729 --> 01:16:09,765
No. I am worried about
what you are saying.

1149
01:16:09,797 --> 01:16:11,800
This kid, Pryor.

1150
01:16:11,832 --> 01:16:13,234
That the East Germans have.
How old is he?

1151
01:16:13,268 --> 01:16:15,671
Twenty-five. Why?

1152
01:16:15,703 --> 01:16:17,703
Same age as Dougie.

1153
01:16:19,207 --> 01:16:20,708
Who?

1154
01:16:20,742 --> 01:16:22,742
An associate of mine.

1155
01:16:24,680 --> 01:16:26,680
Frederic Pryor.

1156
01:18:03,011 --> 01:18:05,011
Okay, okay, okay.

1157
01:19:50,252 --> 01:19:56,024
We apologize if this offends.

1158
01:20:01,363 --> 01:20:03,363
Coat?

1159
01:21:16,971 --> 01:21:20,007
- Do you understand English?
- Yes, Sir.

1160
01:21:20,041 --> 01:21:22,143
I am James Donovan.
I am here to meet a Mr. Vogel.

1161
01:21:22,176 --> 01:21:24,279
Mr. Vogel. He does
not work here.

1162
01:21:24,311 --> 01:21:26,311
I am just supposed to meet
him. That is all I know.

1163
01:21:49,604 --> 01:21:51,604
Mr. Donovan!

1164
01:21:52,106 --> 01:21:54,106
We finally meet you.

1165
01:21:55,609 --> 01:21:57,244
I am Helen Abel.

1166
01:21:57,279 --> 01:21:58,579
- How is my husband?
- He is fine.

1167
01:21:58,613 --> 01:22:00,081
How is my Rudolf?

1168
01:22:00,114 --> 01:22:02,050
As good as, he can be expected.

1169
01:22:02,082 --> 01:22:04,586
We will get him back. Yes.

1170
01:22:04,618 --> 01:22:07,055
- This is our daughter.
- How do you do?

1171
01:22:07,454 --> 01:22:08,454
Lydia.

1172
01:22:09,090 --> 01:22:11,090
Are you Mr. Vogel?

1173
01:22:11,225 --> 01:22:12,560
No, no, no!

1174
01:22:12,594 --> 01:22:14,328
I am not Vogel.

1175
01:22:14,362 --> 01:22:16,362
I am Drew's cousin.

1176
01:22:17,465 --> 01:22:19,333
This is Rudolf's
beloved Drew's cousin.

1177
01:22:19,367 --> 01:22:21,569
- Yes. Drew's cousin.
- I am Drew's cousin.

1178
01:22:21,603 --> 01:22:23,305
Drew's cousin, yes.

1179
01:22:23,337 --> 01:22:25,337
I am Helen Abel.

1180
01:22:28,510 --> 01:22:30,510
When will you see him?

1181
01:22:31,345 --> 01:22:33,347
When will your government
releases him?

1182
01:22:33,381 --> 01:22:35,350
I am a little lost here.

1183
01:22:35,382 --> 01:22:37,252
I am supposed to meet
a Mr. Vogel.

1184
01:22:37,284 --> 01:22:39,386
Mr. Vogel is our lawyer.

1185
01:22:39,421 --> 01:22:43,358
We were supposed to
negotiate the exchange.

1186
01:22:43,390 --> 01:22:46,161
- Do you bring Rudolf here?
- Yes, yes, bring him here.

1187
01:22:46,194 --> 01:22:49,029
It does not happen unilaterally.
Do you understand?

1188
01:22:49,064 --> 01:22:51,064
It has to be an exchange.

1189
01:22:54,202 --> 01:22:56,202
Not here.

1190
01:23:15,689 --> 01:23:17,292
Mr. Donovan?

1191
01:23:17,324 --> 01:23:18,460
Mr. Vogel?

1192
01:23:18,493 --> 01:23:20,395
No, no, no. Goodness.

1193
01:23:20,427 --> 01:23:22,529
My name is Schischkin.
Ivan Schischkin.

1194
01:23:22,564 --> 01:23:24,631
I am the second secretary
of the Soviet embassy.

1195
01:23:25,800 --> 01:23:29,170
It would not be appropriate
for Mr. Vogel to join us.

1196
01:23:29,203 --> 01:23:31,372
He is a German national.

1197
01:23:31,405 --> 01:23:33,608
You are not here to...

1198
01:23:33,640 --> 01:23:37,212
To facilitate this meeting.

1199
01:23:37,244 --> 01:23:40,314
Perhaps Mrs. Abel,

1200
01:23:40,347 --> 01:23:42,516
would like to compose
her privately?

1201
01:23:42,550 --> 01:23:45,520
And let Mr. Donovan
and me to talk.

1202
01:23:47,622 --> 01:23:49,622
Thank you.

1203
01:23:58,533 --> 01:24:01,235
- So, I am confused.
- Yes.

1204
01:24:01,269 --> 01:24:02,703
I do not care
whom I talk to...

1205
01:24:02,737 --> 01:24:06,207
If it is about an
exchange of personnel.

1206
01:24:06,240 --> 01:24:08,208
Are you the person to talk?

1207
01:24:08,243 --> 01:24:11,179
Yes, yes, yes, of course!
We should talk.

1208
01:24:11,212 --> 01:24:13,448
Please, have a seat
Mr. Donovan.

1209
01:24:15,149 --> 01:24:17,351
How did you arrive to
the Eastern sector?

1210
01:24:17,385 --> 01:24:18,453
The train. The S-Bah.

1211
01:24:18,485 --> 01:24:20,255
You were alone.

1212
01:24:20,287 --> 01:24:21,722
Yeah.

1213
01:24:21,756 --> 01:24:25,126
You are credentialed.

1214
01:24:25,159 --> 01:24:27,127
Now, you must know
about me, Sir.

1215
01:24:27,162 --> 01:24:28,662
I am a private citizen.

1216
01:24:28,695 --> 01:24:30,664
I am a lawyer in Brooklyn
in the United States.

1217
01:24:30,698 --> 01:24:33,333
I have taken time out
of my busy schedule.

1218
01:24:33,368 --> 01:24:36,136
To help my client,
Rudolf Abel.

1219
01:24:36,171 --> 01:24:40,207
I authorized to arrange
an exchange of Abel.

1220
01:24:40,240 --> 01:24:42,676
For Francis Gary Powers.

1221
01:24:42,710 --> 01:24:45,579
This is a full pardon of Abel.

1222
01:24:45,613 --> 01:24:47,932
That will be signed when the
exchange actually takes place.

1223
01:24:49,250 --> 01:24:50,618
This is the only
reason I am here.

1224
01:24:50,652 --> 01:24:53,421
I hope and expect to make
this arrangement quickly.

1225
01:24:54,488 --> 01:24:56,524
Abel for Francis Gary Powers.

1226
01:24:58,460 --> 01:25:00,460
And, Frederic Pryor.

1227
01:25:02,463 --> 01:25:04,466
We do not have Pryor.

1228
01:25:04,498 --> 01:25:06,498
No? You do not!

1229
01:25:08,770 --> 01:25:11,439
I have heard of
Pryor, he has held,

1230
01:25:11,472 --> 01:25:14,609
by the German
Democratic Republic.

1231
01:25:14,641 --> 01:25:17,479
Not by the Union of Soviet
Socialist Republics.

1232
01:25:18,412 --> 01:25:21,381
I will tell you the
first problem.

1233
01:25:21,416 --> 01:25:24,418
The names of your
countries are too long.

1234
01:25:24,452 --> 01:25:27,521
Yes, yes.

1235
01:25:28,622 --> 01:25:30,591
If we release Powers.

1236
01:25:30,625 --> 01:25:32,594
It is only to promote
a good will...

1237
01:25:32,627 --> 01:25:34,627
Between our countries.

1238
01:25:35,529 --> 01:25:38,166
So, it cannot be an exchange.

1239
01:25:41,402 --> 01:25:42,604
Perhaps...

1240
01:25:42,636 --> 01:25:45,506
Perhaps you could
release Abel.

1241
01:25:45,539 --> 01:25:47,475
As a token of good will to
our friends in Germany.

1242
01:25:47,509 --> 01:25:50,377
Then, some months later.

1243
01:25:50,411 --> 01:25:52,814
We would release Powers.

1244
01:25:52,846 --> 01:25:55,283
- There is an idea.
- No. That Just will not work for us at all.

1245
01:25:55,315 --> 01:25:57,618
We need this to
be an exchange.

1246
01:25:57,652 --> 01:25:59,420
You can call it
what you want...

1247
01:25:59,453 --> 01:26:01,288
But an exchange it must be.

1248
01:26:01,322 --> 01:26:04,458
We can have Abel here
within 48 hours.

1249
01:26:04,492 --> 01:26:07,962
We need Powers at the same
time. We give you Abel.

1250
01:26:10,863 --> 01:26:12,634
This is...

1251
01:26:12,667 --> 01:26:16,570
Can we call this the
"impatient plan"?

1252
01:26:16,604 --> 01:26:18,604
You can call it
whatever you want.

1253
01:26:20,608 --> 01:26:23,444
I can relay your impatient
plan to Moscow.

1254
01:26:23,478 --> 01:26:24,345
See what they say...

1255
01:26:24,378 --> 01:26:29,114
They will wonder
why so impatient.

1256
01:26:29,317 --> 01:26:30,717
Because I have a cold.

1257
01:26:30,752 --> 01:26:32,752
I do not live in Berlin.
I want to go home.

1258
01:26:33,621 --> 01:26:34,721
They will think...

1259
01:26:34,756 --> 01:26:37,591
"Well, the Americans
must have gotten..."

1260
01:26:37,625 --> 01:26:40,561
"All the information
that Abel had to give."

1261
01:26:40,595 --> 01:26:44,399
"And now they are
impatient to trade him."

1262
01:26:44,431 --> 01:26:47,467
"Hoping to get in return
this man Powers."

1263
01:26:47,502 --> 01:26:49,604
"Perhaps, has not
yet given up..."

1264
01:26:49,636 --> 01:26:51,639
"All the information
that he has to give."

1265
01:26:53,507 --> 01:26:55,643
This is not an
equitable trade, Sir.

1266
01:26:56,911 --> 01:26:58,546
What you are saying is...

1267
01:26:58,579 --> 01:27:00,582
If Powers has given up
everything, he knows.

1268
01:27:00,614 --> 01:27:02,850
Then Moscow would trade?

1269
01:27:02,884 --> 01:27:04,884
Why would not they?

1270
01:27:05,619 --> 01:27:08,655
As for Abel, if he dies
in an American prison.

1271
01:27:08,689 --> 01:27:11,359
The next Russian
operative who is caught.

1272
01:27:11,391 --> 01:27:13,427
Might think twice about
keeping his mouth shut.

1273
01:27:13,461 --> 01:27:18,800
You never know. Abel might
want to see the sky again.

1274
01:27:18,832 --> 01:27:21,868
And, decide to trade Russian
secrets for small American favors.

1275
01:27:25,707 --> 01:27:27,774
How can we know this?

1276
01:27:27,809 --> 01:27:31,479
We are little man.
We just do our jobs.

1277
01:27:31,511 --> 01:27:33,847
Like Lieutenant Powers.
He is just a pilot.

1278
01:27:36,684 --> 01:27:40,520
He was making photographs
from 70,000 feet.

1279
01:27:40,555 --> 01:27:42,555
When he has shot from the sky.

1280
01:27:42,689 --> 01:27:44,759
People in my country
consider this...

1281
01:27:44,792 --> 01:27:46,792
An act of war.

1282
01:27:48,962 --> 01:27:51,733
We have to get off this
merry-go-round, Sir.

1283
01:27:51,765 --> 01:27:53,533
The next mistake our
countries make...

1284
01:27:53,568 --> 01:27:55,568
Could be the last one.

1285
01:27:56,537 --> 01:27:58,805
We need to have
the conversation.

1286
01:27:58,840 --> 01:28:00,840
Our governments cannot.

1287
01:28:05,846 --> 01:28:08,515
I will ask Moscow.

1288
01:28:08,548 --> 01:28:10,548
Who knows, what they will say.

1289
01:28:12,453 --> 01:28:13,787
There are many people,
Mr. Donovan.

1290
01:28:13,820 --> 01:28:17,925
Who does not want this
exchange ever takes place.

1291
01:28:20,862 --> 01:28:24,399
Can you come back tomorrow
to discuss their answer?

1292
01:28:24,431 --> 01:28:25,432
Powers for Abel.

1293
01:28:25,466 --> 01:28:26,934
And, Frederic Pryor.

1294
01:28:26,967 --> 01:28:28,469
As I said...

1295
01:28:28,502 --> 01:28:30,671
Pryor is in the hands
of the organs...

1296
01:28:30,704 --> 01:28:32,907
State Security of the
German Democratic Republic.

1297
01:28:32,939 --> 01:28:35,510
I am confident. You can
make arrangements.

1298
01:28:35,542 --> 01:28:37,845
I am merely a secretary.

1299
01:28:37,878 --> 01:28:39,579
In the embassy of
foreign Powers.

1300
01:28:39,613 --> 01:28:40,948
Okay.

1301
01:28:40,981 --> 01:28:44,585
You have to see Mr. Vogel.
I will give you his address.

1302
01:28:44,618 --> 01:28:46,554
There actually is a Mr. Vogel?

1303
01:28:46,587 --> 01:28:48,855
Why would you
imagine otherwise?

1304
01:28:48,890 --> 01:28:50,890
It is a short cab ride.

1305
01:28:51,993 --> 01:28:54,828
Please, Mr. Donovan...

1306
01:28:54,862 --> 01:28:56,862
Wear an overcoat
in this weather.

1307
01:28:58,498 --> 01:29:00,498
I had my stolen from me.

1308
01:29:01,034 --> 01:29:02,703
What do you expect?

1309
01:29:02,737 --> 01:29:04,737
It was from Saks Fifth Avenue.

1310
01:29:05,907 --> 01:29:07,907
Was not it?

1311
01:29:15,649 --> 01:29:16,984
<i>Mr. Donovan.</i>

1312
01:29:17,018 --> 01:29:18,453
Mr. Vogel.

1313
01:29:18,485 --> 01:29:21,185
<i>- Please, come in.
- Ok.</i>

1314
01:29:24,958 --> 01:29:26,958
Sorry about the embassy.

1315
01:29:28,796 --> 01:29:30,796
The Soviets decided
not to host me.

1316
01:29:32,533 --> 01:29:34,435
That is very irritating.

1317
01:29:34,469 --> 01:29:36,770
I am still trying to
grasp each party is...

1318
01:29:37,738 --> 01:29:39,506
Status?

1319
01:29:39,539 --> 01:29:42,643
Yes. And, interest
in the proceedings.

1320
01:29:43,778 --> 01:29:45,712
It is a new world.

1321
01:29:45,747 --> 01:29:47,782
All are very disorienting.
Is not it?

1322
01:29:58,091 --> 01:30:00,091
Let me tell you what
I have to offer.

1323
01:30:02,697 --> 01:30:04,532
I am a good friend...

1324
01:30:04,564 --> 01:30:06,600
- "Friend."
- No, he is older.

1325
01:30:06,634 --> 01:30:08,536
"Protege"?

1326
01:30:08,569 --> 01:30:11,037
Of the attorney general of the
German Democratic Republic.

1327
01:30:11,072 --> 01:30:13,072
Sit down, please.

1328
01:30:15,676 --> 01:30:17,545
This is unfortunate.

1329
01:30:17,578 --> 01:30:19,780
Frederic Pryor.

1330
01:30:19,814 --> 01:30:22,317
He was in the wrong place
at the wrong time.

1331
01:30:22,750 --> 01:30:25,819
But every accident,
properly viewed...

1332
01:30:25,853 --> 01:30:27,954
Is an opportunity?
Is not it, Mr. Donovan?

1333
01:30:27,988 --> 01:30:30,957
Your country refuses
to recognize.

1334
01:30:30,992 --> 01:30:33,661
The German
Democratic Republic.

1335
01:30:33,694 --> 01:30:35,695
They prefer to
make up stories.

1336
01:30:35,729 --> 01:30:37,729
That the G.D.R does not
exist, for instance.

1337
01:30:39,699 --> 01:30:41,699
Sorry.

1338
01:30:41,769 --> 01:30:44,104
As a means of forcing your
Government's recognition...

1339
01:30:44,137 --> 01:30:46,673
this real place. Sir.

1340
01:30:46,707 --> 01:30:48,576
In which you find yourself...

1341
01:30:48,609 --> 01:30:50,077
The G.D.R.

1342
01:30:50,110 --> 01:30:52,579
The attorney general is happy
to negotiate with you.

1343
01:30:52,613 --> 01:30:54,849
As a representative
of your government.

1344
01:30:54,881 --> 01:30:56,117
For Mr. Pryor return.

1345
01:30:56,149 --> 01:30:57,717
Mr. Vogel, I am not here.

1346
01:30:57,752 --> 01:30:59,787
As a representative
of my government.

1347
01:31:02,856 --> 01:31:04,856
All right!

1348
01:31:06,860 --> 01:31:09,029
I think that is childish,
Mr. Donovan.

1349
01:31:09,063 --> 01:31:11,698
I have no official status.

1350
01:31:11,731 --> 01:31:13,100
Fine.

1351
01:31:13,134 --> 01:31:15,936
You do not represent the USA.
I do not represent the G.D.R.

1352
01:31:15,970 --> 01:31:18,604
My client is Lydia
Abel, Rudolf's wife.

1353
01:31:18,738 --> 01:31:19,739
And, I have...

1354
01:31:19,774 --> 01:31:21,842
Lydia is the daughter.
Helen is the wife.

1355
01:31:27,782 --> 01:31:29,782
Well...

1356
01:31:30,685 --> 01:31:32,086
I am prepared to offer...

1357
01:31:32,118 --> 01:31:34,988
Frederic Pryor in exchange
for Rudolf Abel.

1358
01:31:36,724 --> 01:31:38,024
Then let us be clear.

1359
01:31:38,059 --> 01:31:40,161
We will produce Rudolf Abel.

1360
01:31:40,194 --> 01:31:43,564
You will produce, at the same
time, the student, Pryor.

1361
01:31:44,097 --> 01:31:45,600
At the same time?

1362
01:31:45,632 --> 01:31:47,068
Absolutely.

1363
01:31:47,100 --> 01:31:51,671
The exchange on offer is a
Russian at the end of his life.

1364
01:31:53,975 --> 01:31:56,743
For an American student
at the start of his.

1365
01:32:03,684 --> 01:32:06,654
Schischkin? He is not a
secretary of embassy.

1366
01:32:06,686 --> 01:32:09,657
Ivan Schischkin is the chief
of KGB in western Europe.

1367
01:32:09,689 --> 01:32:10,992
Whatever he is...

1368
01:32:11,024 --> 01:32:13,927
He is relaying our
proposal to Moscow.

1369
01:32:15,762 --> 01:32:16,930
And, they will decide.

1370
01:32:16,963 --> 01:32:19,734
Can I borrow your coat?
I lost mine.

1371
01:32:19,766 --> 01:32:21,202
How did you lose your coat?

1372
01:32:21,234 --> 01:32:23,234
You know, spy stuff.

1373
01:32:25,706 --> 01:32:28,708
- I will get you another coat.
- Good, because...

1374
01:32:28,743 --> 01:32:30,912
Who is...? Who is this Vogel?

1375
01:32:31,811 --> 01:32:33,613
He... We do not know.

1376
01:32:33,648 --> 01:32:35,917
He might be what
you said he is.

1377
01:32:35,949 --> 01:32:37,184
Friend of the
attorney general.

1378
01:32:37,217 --> 01:32:40,921
Just some person the G.D.R
tapped to handle this.

1379
01:32:40,954 --> 01:32:42,856
Sounds like the East Germans...

1380
01:32:42,890 --> 01:32:45,626
are fighting for a
place at our table.

1381
01:32:45,659 --> 01:32:48,695
<i>The G.D.R gets Abel back
for the Russians...</i>

1382
01:32:48,729 --> 01:32:49,896
winning their respect...

1383
01:32:49,930 --> 01:32:52,699
capturing the headlines
for their cause.

1384
01:32:52,733 --> 01:32:54,969
Which puts the East Germany
on the map.

1385
01:32:55,002 --> 01:32:57,704
We do not care
about their map.

1386
01:32:57,738 --> 01:32:59,206
Stick to the Russians.

1387
01:32:59,239 --> 01:33:01,841
Stick to the Russians.
It is Powers for Abel.

1388
01:33:01,876 --> 01:33:05,011
What does all mean?
This might actually happen.

1389
01:33:05,046 --> 01:33:06,913
Yeah. That is what you
seem to be telling me.

1390
01:33:06,948 --> 01:33:09,984
We will put Abel on a plane.
He will be here Friday.

1391
01:33:10,016 --> 01:33:12,019
So, if Schischkin gets the okay.

1392
01:33:12,052 --> 01:33:14,220
All that is the mechanics
of the trade.

1393
01:33:14,255 --> 01:33:16,090
How we swap our person
for their person.

1394
01:33:16,122 --> 01:33:18,225
Our "guys." Two people.

1395
01:33:18,259 --> 01:33:20,728
Powers and Pryor.

1396
01:33:20,761 --> 01:33:23,698
No. Now do not go
bleeding heart on me.

1397
01:33:23,730 --> 01:33:25,932
Powers is the whole ball game.

1398
01:33:25,966 --> 01:33:27,734
Forget this Ivy League boy.

1399
01:33:27,768 --> 01:33:29,869
Obviously it was a good idea.

1400
01:33:29,904 --> 01:33:32,273
To study Soviet
Economics in Berlin.

1401
01:33:32,305 --> 01:33:34,305
In the middle of the Cold War.

1402
01:33:35,775 --> 01:33:37,775
Powers is whom we need.

1403
01:33:38,145 --> 01:33:40,145
You do not even like Powers.

1404
01:33:41,215 --> 01:33:43,884
Everybody hates Powers.

1405
01:33:43,917 --> 01:33:48,122
He did not kill himself and he let
the commies parade on television.

1406
01:33:48,154 --> 01:33:50,690
He is the most hated
man in America.

1407
01:33:50,725 --> 01:33:53,226
After Rudolf Abel, maybe.

1408
01:33:53,260 --> 01:33:55,260
And me.

1409
01:34:03,938 --> 01:34:05,938
Now wake up! Come out.

1410
01:34:14,047 --> 01:34:15,916
I have to sleep.

1411
01:34:15,949 --> 01:34:17,949
I just have to sleep.

1412
01:34:20,954 --> 01:34:22,122
I told you could sleep.

1413
01:34:22,155 --> 01:34:23,990
Once we talk what
need to talk.

1414
01:34:24,024 --> 01:34:26,860
You must focus on me.

1415
01:34:26,894 --> 01:34:29,262
Your government does not care
about you. You know that.

1416
01:34:29,296 --> 01:34:30,497
Any of you.

1417
01:34:30,530 --> 01:34:34,201
You know that 12 U-2 pilots
incurred brain damage.

1418
01:34:34,234 --> 01:34:37,805
They are vegetables because of
altitude, insufficient oxygen.

1419
01:34:37,837 --> 01:34:39,806
<i>They keep you flying, Gary.</i>

1420
01:34:39,840 --> 01:34:41,908
<i>You and your friends.</i>

1421
01:34:41,942 --> 01:34:45,345
They gave you this,
a scratchier.

1422
01:34:45,378 --> 01:34:48,149
Potassium Cyanide.

1423
01:34:48,181 --> 01:34:51,118
Does that look like
they care about you?

1424
01:35:20,213 --> 01:35:23,783
What is the construction
of the destructor unit?

1425
01:35:23,818 --> 01:35:25,853
What means is this
unit working?

1426
01:35:25,886 --> 01:35:28,988
With what explosives
the unit charges.

1427
01:35:29,023 --> 01:35:31,023
What destruction
is it capable?

1428
01:35:31,425 --> 01:35:33,394
I do not know.

1429
01:35:33,426 --> 01:35:35,829
They never showed any of the
equipment to the pilots.

1430
01:35:35,863 --> 01:35:38,131
How far can the radar hide?

1431
01:35:38,164 --> 01:35:40,067
An area on map during flight.

1432
01:35:40,100 --> 01:35:41,101
I do not know! I do not know!

1433
01:35:41,135 --> 01:35:45,105
And you were making the
flight on April 9?

1434
01:35:45,139 --> 01:35:47,841
On the industrial area
and MIR bomber base.

1435
01:35:47,875 --> 01:35:48,943
At Baranovichi.

1436
01:35:48,975 --> 01:35:50,877
I was not.

1437
01:35:50,911 --> 01:35:52,179
This was my first flight.

1438
01:35:52,412 --> 01:35:56,250
I need to know about of
engine out glide to the ratio.

1439
01:35:56,283 --> 01:35:59,319
How the plane gets so high.

1440
01:35:59,353 --> 01:36:04,291
We know it reaches
altitude of 70,000 feet.

1441
01:36:04,324 --> 01:36:06,260
Gary, we know this.

1442
01:36:06,292 --> 01:36:08,895
I need to know where
the planes have flown.

1443
01:36:08,929 --> 01:36:11,297
Where they have flown, Gary.

1444
01:36:11,332 --> 01:36:13,332
We must have this talk now.

1445
01:36:16,203 --> 01:36:18,139
Now.

1446
01:36:18,171 --> 01:36:20,841
Then you can sleep a little.

1447
01:36:25,045 --> 01:36:27,045
<i>Sir, wake up.</i>

1448
01:36:28,282 --> 01:36:30,282
Wake up, Sir.

1449
01:36:32,153 --> 01:36:34,121
- Sir, can you come with me, please?
- Yeah.

1450
01:36:34,154 --> 01:36:36,189
- We have to move.
- Yeah, of course!

1451
01:36:36,222 --> 01:36:37,457
- Can you come with me, please?
- Yeah.

1452
01:36:37,490 --> 01:36:39,490
Okay.

1453
01:36:40,127 --> 01:36:41,929
Take your glasses.

1454
01:36:41,962 --> 01:36:45,198
- What time is it?
- It is late but, we need to talk.

1455
01:36:45,231 --> 01:36:47,231
We need that you get
in a plane, okay?

1456
01:36:48,068 --> 01:36:50,171
Yeah. Upsy-daisy!

1457
01:36:50,203 --> 01:36:52,105
- Upsy-daisy.
- That is right.

1458
01:36:52,139 --> 01:36:53,407
There we go. Keep moving.

1459
01:36:53,439 --> 01:36:55,439
Thank you.

1460
01:36:57,177 --> 01:36:58,878
Other way, other way.

1461
01:36:58,912 --> 01:36:59,947
There we go.

1462
01:36:59,979 --> 01:37:01,215
You say a plane.

1463
01:37:01,247 --> 01:37:03,117
This way, please. Keep moving.

1464
01:37:03,149 --> 01:37:06,119
<i>So, I received a
favorable decision.</i>

1465
01:37:06,153 --> 01:37:08,221
<i>From Moscow on your proposal.</i>

1466
01:37:08,255 --> 01:37:11,225
<i>That we help our friends in the
German Democratic Republic.</i>

1467
01:37:11,492 --> 01:37:13,260
By exchanging.

1468
01:37:13,293 --> 01:37:15,293
Mr. Powers for Mr. Abel.

1469
01:37:17,264 --> 01:37:18,498
That is well.

1470
01:37:18,532 --> 01:37:23,103
May I suggest the Glienicke
Bridge as a place of exchange?

1471
01:37:23,136 --> 01:37:24,404
Why not Checkpoint Charlie?

1472
01:37:24,438 --> 01:37:27,106
We are not looking
for publicity.

1473
01:37:27,140 --> 01:37:29,076
The Glienicke Bridge
is very quiet.

1474
01:37:29,109 --> 01:37:30,377
Especially early
in the morning.

1475
01:37:30,411 --> 01:37:33,180
Glienicke Bridge.
I will run to our side.

1476
01:37:33,213 --> 01:37:34,981
We can have Abel
here on Friday.

1477
01:37:35,015 --> 01:37:36,317
So, Saturday morning.

1478
01:37:36,350 --> 01:37:38,385
Always impatience, yeah.

1479
01:37:38,418 --> 01:37:40,054
I want to get home,
go into my bed.

1480
01:37:40,087 --> 01:37:42,355
So, Saturday morning.

1481
01:37:42,389 --> 01:37:43,990
5:30 p.m.

1482
01:37:44,024 --> 01:37:45,525
All right!

1483
01:37:45,559 --> 01:37:47,261
We have done here.

1484
01:37:47,293 --> 01:37:48,529
This is a number.

1485
01:37:48,561 --> 01:37:51,998
In case, anything
should come up.

1486
01:37:52,032 --> 01:37:53,132
All right!

1487
01:37:53,167 --> 01:37:55,167
Someone will answer
at any hour.

1488
01:37:56,203 --> 01:37:58,203
I do not expect to use it.

1489
01:37:59,105 --> 01:38:01,408
Shall we toast
the arrangement?

1490
01:38:01,442 --> 01:38:03,442
Why not?

1491
01:38:04,578 --> 01:38:06,113
Armenian Brandy.

1492
01:38:06,145 --> 01:38:08,145
- Good for your cold.
- Thank you.

1493
01:38:09,082 --> 01:38:10,283
Would you mind...?

1494
01:38:10,317 --> 01:38:12,152
This is not part
of our business.

1495
01:38:12,185 --> 01:38:14,421
I would like to ask you
a couple of questions.

1496
01:38:14,454 --> 01:38:16,155
You do not have to answer.

1497
01:38:16,189 --> 01:38:18,189
I have the answer what I know.

1498
01:38:18,391 --> 01:38:21,427
I like this person,
your person.

1499
01:38:21,462 --> 01:38:24,364
What happens to your person.
When he gets home.

1500
01:38:24,398 --> 01:38:26,399
We have to make a
determination.

1501
01:38:26,432 --> 01:38:29,103
Whether our person
is now your person.

1502
01:38:29,136 --> 01:38:31,005
Now, as I said to you before...

1503
01:38:31,037 --> 01:38:32,273
He has acted honorably.

1504
01:38:32,305 --> 01:38:34,041
He is still your person,
believe me.

1505
01:38:34,073 --> 01:38:37,043
Of course! You will
say if it were true.

1506
01:38:37,077 --> 01:38:39,279
If it were not true.

1507
01:38:39,313 --> 01:38:41,582
I guess it has come down.

1508
01:38:41,614 --> 01:38:43,317
Well, forgive me for pushing.

1509
01:38:43,350 --> 01:38:46,185
But is he in any danger?

1510
01:38:46,220 --> 01:38:48,521
If the determination is made.

1511
01:38:48,555 --> 01:38:50,990
Well, goodness.

1512
01:38:51,024 --> 01:38:53,594
As things are now,
everyone is in danger.

1513
01:38:53,627 --> 01:38:55,627
Cheers.

1514
01:39:09,342 --> 01:39:11,342
There will be no exchange
on Glienicke Bridge.

1515
01:39:12,378 --> 01:39:14,314
Excuse me, Sir.

1516
01:39:14,347 --> 01:39:16,382
There will be no exchange.

1517
01:39:17,251 --> 01:39:19,118
Not for Frederic Pryor.

1518
01:39:19,153 --> 01:39:22,256
Mr. Vogel, I thought
yesterday we have agreed.

1519
01:39:22,288 --> 01:39:24,524
We agreed on an exchange,
Abel for Pryor.

1520
01:39:26,260 --> 01:39:29,395
Now I learn, you are
a rug merchant.

1521
01:39:29,430 --> 01:39:32,298
Selling the same rug
to two customers.

1522
01:39:32,332 --> 01:39:35,202
- Abel for Pryor you sell to us.
- Yeah.

1523
01:39:35,234 --> 01:39:37,438
Abel for Powers you
sell to the Soviets.

1524
01:39:37,470 --> 01:39:40,106
I am not very sure,
the problem is...

1525
01:39:40,140 --> 01:39:43,144
If the arrangement satisfies
two parties, three, or four.

1526
01:39:43,277 --> 01:39:44,411
What difference does make?

1527
01:39:44,545 --> 01:39:46,545
The arrangement does
not satisfy this part.

1528
01:39:51,104 --> 01:39:53,104
Now, Mr. Vogel, please...

1529
01:39:53,153 --> 01:39:56,389
Obviously, you do not know
who with you are dealing.

1530
01:39:57,457 --> 01:40:00,094
The interest of the German
Democratic Republic.

1531
01:40:01,395 --> 01:40:02,595
To deal with...

1532
01:40:02,628 --> 01:40:05,498
Is it seems dealing with
another sovereign power?

1533
01:40:05,532 --> 01:40:07,167
The United States.

1534
01:40:07,201 --> 01:40:09,269
An equal power.

1535
01:40:09,302 --> 01:40:10,671
Instead, you treat
us as stooges.

1536
01:40:10,703 --> 01:40:12,672
For the Union of Soviet
Socialist Republics.

1537
01:40:12,706 --> 01:40:15,109
Can we just call them the
Russians? It will save time.

1538
01:40:16,577 --> 01:40:18,545
I have an appointment, Sir.

1539
01:40:18,578 --> 01:40:20,346
I think you are wasting time.

1540
01:40:20,381 --> 01:40:22,416
Now, tell me if I am
describing this wrong.

1541
01:40:22,448 --> 01:40:24,184
You have a kid, a
university student.

1542
01:40:24,217 --> 01:40:25,551
Someone knows he is not a spy.

1543
01:40:25,586 --> 01:40:27,087
Who have not threat to you?

1544
01:40:27,121 --> 01:40:28,555
In exchange for this person.

1545
01:40:28,588 --> 01:40:30,323
Who is worthless to you?

1546
01:40:30,356 --> 01:40:32,525
You play an equal
part in an exchange.

1547
01:40:32,559 --> 01:40:34,627
Between the Russians
and, the Americans.

1548
01:40:34,661 --> 01:40:39,166
And this is one transaction
between two of you and us.

1549
01:40:39,198 --> 01:40:40,634
We are not trying to do
two things here, Sir.

1550
01:40:40,667 --> 01:40:42,368
We are just doing one thing.
One, one, one.

1551
01:40:42,403 --> 01:40:47,474
It is hard for me to see, how the Republic
of East German Democrats has been slighted.

1552
01:40:47,507 --> 01:40:50,377
You agreed with the Soviets
without consulting me.

1553
01:40:50,411 --> 01:40:52,345
Is this a negotiation
or a conspiracy?

1554
01:40:52,378 --> 01:40:53,279
For it to be a conspiracy...

1555
01:40:53,313 --> 01:40:54,480
There would have to
be harm to you, Sir.

1556
01:40:54,515 --> 01:40:57,451
There are just benefits here.
We are of agreeing interests.

1557
01:40:57,484 --> 01:40:59,484
No. You decide they agree.

1558
01:41:00,421 --> 01:41:02,155
Where is your
appointment, sir?

1559
01:41:02,189 --> 01:41:03,590
In the West.

1560
01:41:03,623 --> 01:41:05,623
Good.

1561
01:41:15,769 --> 01:41:16,936
<i>Look around you.</i>

1562
01:41:16,970 --> 01:41:20,474
How does the Eastern sector
to compare the West?

1563
01:41:22,509 --> 01:41:24,478
Our Russian friends
have decided that...

1564
01:41:24,511 --> 01:41:26,511
We should not rebuild
our capital city.

1565
01:41:28,715 --> 01:41:32,219
We live in this ruin made
by our Russian friends.

1566
01:41:32,252 --> 01:41:34,252
Go ahead. Make your deal
with these Russians.

1567
01:41:34,753 --> 01:41:36,753
We will not be part of it.

1568
01:41:38,323 --> 01:41:39,524
There is no deal
without Pryor.

1569
01:41:39,658 --> 01:41:40,626
We are not leaving him here.

1570
01:41:40,760 --> 01:41:41,761
Is this your position
or of your government?

1571
01:41:41,795 --> 01:41:45,565
Sir, I am here.
I am talking to you.

1572
01:41:45,599 --> 01:41:47,533
You are not a representative
of your government.

1573
01:41:47,568 --> 01:41:50,270
They do not know who you are.
Neither do we.

1574
01:41:50,304 --> 01:41:52,605
You should be careful. This
is not Brooklyn, Mr. Donovan.

1575
01:42:00,279 --> 01:42:01,681
Look, Sir.

1576
01:42:01,715 --> 01:42:03,550
You must know every
respect that matters.

1577
01:42:03,583 --> 01:42:05,583
I represent my government.

1578
01:42:05,786 --> 01:42:07,786
You know who I am.

1579
01:42:08,421 --> 01:42:10,421
Do I know?

1580
01:42:31,545 --> 01:42:34,381
Do you have the proper papers?

1581
01:42:34,413 --> 01:42:37,283
Of course not. It
does not matter.

1582
01:42:37,317 --> 01:42:38,484
An American lawyer like you.

1583
01:42:38,519 --> 01:42:40,287
Can talk your way of anything?

1584
01:42:40,319 --> 01:42:42,319
Cannot you?

1585
01:43:24,331 --> 01:43:26,265
You go with him. Sir.

1586
01:43:26,300 --> 01:43:28,801
- Why?
- It is passport problem.

1587
01:43:28,835 --> 01:43:30,104
What... What is the problem?
What is the problem?

1588
01:43:30,436 --> 01:43:34,436
- You go with him.
- Sir. Come with us.

1589
01:43:34,541 --> 01:43:35,876
And, remember...

1590
01:43:35,908 --> 01:43:37,908
We control the fate
of Frederic Pryor.

1591
01:45:22,548 --> 01:45:24,548
My God!

1592
01:45:59,219 --> 01:46:01,654
Yeah. I will start with
some coffee, please.

1593
01:46:01,688 --> 01:46:03,856
Then I will have
the Hilton Combo.

1594
01:46:03,890 --> 01:46:05,725
The American breakfast.

1595
01:46:05,759 --> 01:46:06,859
And, coffee.

1596
01:46:06,893 --> 01:46:07,961
Both breakfasts?

1597
01:46:07,993 --> 01:46:09,529
Yeah, yeah.

1598
01:46:09,563 --> 01:46:10,764
One first or...

1599
01:46:10,796 --> 01:46:12,498
Both first, both.
When they are ready.

1600
01:46:12,532 --> 01:46:14,532
And, coffee.

1601
01:46:32,085 --> 01:46:33,854
You should not be here.

1602
01:46:33,886 --> 01:46:35,055
Well, sometimes in Germany.

1603
01:46:35,087 --> 01:46:37,087
You just want a big
American breakfast.

1604
01:46:41,027 --> 01:46:43,063
What happened?
Where were you last night?

1605
01:46:43,095 --> 01:46:46,065
Vogel arranged for me to
spend some time in the East.

1606
01:46:46,099 --> 01:46:47,667
Jesus!

1607
01:46:47,701 --> 01:46:48,935
Frankly, it is not
that much worse.

1608
01:46:48,969 --> 01:46:50,969
Than where you have
me here in the West.

1609
01:46:52,872 --> 01:46:56,542
The Russians are fine
with the exchange.

1610
01:46:56,576 --> 01:46:59,078
Now Vogel is saying that the
East Germans will not do it.

1611
01:46:59,112 --> 01:47:01,112
We are not going to get Pryor.

1612
01:47:01,515 --> 01:47:03,516
Great. Good.

1613
01:47:03,550 --> 01:47:05,551
So, the Soviets are set.
We get Powers.

1614
01:47:05,585 --> 01:47:06,853
We get Powers.

1615
01:47:06,886 --> 01:47:08,889
Well done!

1616
01:47:08,921 --> 01:47:10,957
No. The East Germans
will not do it.

1617
01:47:10,990 --> 01:47:13,092
We will not get Pryor,
and that kid matters.

1618
01:47:13,126 --> 01:47:14,828
Every person matters.

1619
01:47:14,860 --> 01:47:17,898
Sure. That is why you tried.
That is why you tried.

1620
01:47:17,930 --> 01:47:19,966
Abel is on his way, so we are
all set for tomorrow morning.

1621
01:47:20,000 --> 01:47:22,569
- Wait a minute.
- Makes the things simple.

1622
01:47:22,601 --> 01:47:24,871
We are not getting the kid.

1623
01:47:24,904 --> 01:47:27,039
Yeah. I understand.
We are set.

1624
01:47:27,073 --> 01:47:29,073
We can ignore the message.
We got this morning.

1625
01:47:30,676 --> 01:47:31,912
What is message?

1626
01:47:31,944 --> 01:47:33,078
From the East Germans.

1627
01:47:33,113 --> 01:47:35,047
They called the number.
I gave you.

1628
01:47:35,081 --> 01:47:37,583
They said that wanted
to speak to you today.

1629
01:47:37,617 --> 01:47:39,586
- Vogel called.
- No.

1630
01:47:39,618 --> 01:47:41,954
An Officer of Harold Ott.

1631
01:47:41,988 --> 01:47:43,556
East German attorney general.

1632
01:47:43,590 --> 01:47:45,057
What does he want?
What does he want?

1633
01:47:45,091 --> 01:47:46,193
Well, to talk to you.

1634
01:47:46,225 --> 01:47:49,128
It is ok. I cannot ask
you to go back there.

1635
01:47:49,162 --> 01:47:51,765
Listen, you seem to be a persona
non grata to some elements.

1636
01:47:51,997 --> 01:47:53,099
We will not push our luck.

1637
01:47:53,132 --> 01:47:55,135
So, he wants to see me.

1638
01:47:55,167 --> 01:47:56,103
What time?

1639
01:47:57,136 --> 01:48:00,073
No. No. Now, listen. You... You...

1640
01:48:00,105 --> 01:48:02,141
You... You do not need to go.
In fact you should not go.

1641
01:48:02,175 --> 01:48:04,610
In fact, you cannot go.

1642
01:48:04,644 --> 01:48:06,979
We set with the Soviets.
We do not want to screw it up.

1643
01:48:07,012 --> 01:48:08,948
- I am not going to screw it up.
- You are not going!

1644
01:48:08,981 --> 01:48:10,550
Do not be a pain in the ass.

1645
01:48:10,583 --> 01:48:11,952
I ordered.

1646
01:48:11,984 --> 01:48:14,054
Enjoy your big
American breakfast.

1647
01:48:23,796 --> 01:48:25,731
I thought it should be negotiated.

1648
01:48:25,765 --> 01:48:27,967
At the highest level
as a courtesy to you.

1649
01:48:28,001 --> 01:48:30,001
Thank you, Sir.

1650
01:48:32,037 --> 01:48:34,908
I do not know how things
became so confused.

1651
01:48:34,940 --> 01:48:37,743
Well! I guess sometimes
they just became.

1652
01:48:42,215 --> 01:48:43,817
For sake of clarity.

1653
01:48:43,850 --> 01:48:46,185
I say, we are fully
prepared to exchange.

1654
01:48:46,219 --> 01:48:50,923
They called student
Pryor, for Rudolf Abel.

1655
01:48:50,957 --> 01:48:53,792
I understand Mr. Vogel that
Pryor is very important to you.

1656
01:48:53,827 --> 01:48:55,194
Yes, but...

1657
01:48:55,228 --> 01:48:57,796
We will do a memorandum
to that effect.

1658
01:48:59,164 --> 01:49:01,100
A memorandum.

1659
01:49:01,134 --> 01:49:04,604
Certainly, we commit a
bi-lateral exchange.

1660
01:49:06,139 --> 01:49:10,676
Yes, yes, sure. I am not sure.
What that means but...

1661
01:49:10,710 --> 01:49:15,081
My country also insists
on Francis Gary Powers.

1662
01:49:15,114 --> 01:49:17,114
No!

1663
01:49:21,253 --> 01:49:24,925
This is how things
became so confused.

1664
01:49:24,957 --> 01:49:27,694
Powers. What use is he, Sir?

1665
01:49:27,726 --> 01:49:29,628
You want him back for
punitive reasons.

1666
01:49:29,662 --> 01:49:30,863
What has done has done.

1667
01:49:30,896 --> 01:49:32,198
He has divulged. What
will he divulge?

1668
01:49:32,231 --> 01:49:35,034
As no doubt, Abel has also.

1669
01:49:35,068 --> 01:49:39,838
We are offering instead someone,
whom you insist is innocent.

1670
01:49:39,872 --> 01:49:41,173
And, this is right.

1671
01:49:41,207 --> 01:49:43,207
This is whom you
should retrieve.

1672
01:49:43,275 --> 01:49:44,911
The future.

1673
01:49:44,944 --> 01:49:46,944
Look to the future.

1674
01:50:04,163 --> 01:50:06,166
I am sorry. Could you
give me a moment, Sir?

1675
01:50:26,152 --> 01:50:28,287
I am very sorry, Sir.
The attorney general regrets.

1676
01:50:28,320 --> 01:50:30,990
That he had to leave
on urgent business.

1677
01:50:31,024 --> 01:50:34,260
- He left.
- Yes. Many apologies.

1678
01:50:34,293 --> 01:50:36,695
I have been waiting
for him over an hour.

1679
01:50:36,729 --> 01:50:38,729
Very sorry, Sir.

1680
01:50:40,300 --> 01:50:42,300
Young man?

1681
01:50:43,936 --> 01:50:45,936
Come here.

1682
01:50:46,805 --> 01:50:48,805
It is all right! Come here.

1683
01:50:54,779 --> 01:50:56,779
Take a seat.

1684
01:50:58,083 --> 01:51:00,083
Come on! Come on! Sit down.

1685
01:51:04,224 --> 01:51:06,224
Do you like your job here?

1686
01:51:06,826 --> 01:51:08,194
It is a very good job, Sir.

1687
01:51:08,228 --> 01:51:10,329
It must be...
It must be interesting.

1688
01:51:10,363 --> 01:51:11,797
Yes, Sir.

1689
01:51:11,831 --> 01:51:13,932
And, important too.

1690
01:51:13,966 --> 01:51:16,935
Your English is... Is good.

1691
01:51:16,970 --> 01:51:18,971
Yes. I hesitate to
say it is excellent.

1692
01:51:19,005 --> 01:51:19,872
It is excellent, Sir.

1693
01:51:19,905 --> 01:51:21,940
Good, good. Good.

1694
01:51:21,975 --> 01:51:24,877
I just lost my
negotiating partner.

1695
01:51:24,911 --> 01:51:26,945
And, I need somebody to talk.

1696
01:51:26,979 --> 01:51:28,979
You seem like a
reasonable young man.

1697
01:51:30,216 --> 01:51:32,216
Can I talk to you?

1698
01:51:35,020 --> 01:51:36,256
It is all right!

1699
01:51:36,288 --> 01:51:38,288
It is all right! I just...

1700
01:51:40,159 --> 01:51:42,228
I just need you to give
a message to your boss.

1701
01:51:44,797 --> 01:51:46,797
It has to be very,
very, very clear.

1702
01:51:47,833 --> 01:51:49,833
Do you understand?

1703
01:51:50,170 --> 01:51:53,305
Yes, Sir. But perhaps you
should wait until him.

1704
01:51:53,338 --> 01:51:56,810
No, no. The thing is. I have this
cold and I want to get home.

1705
01:51:57,342 --> 01:51:59,342
And, get in bed.

1706
01:52:00,979 --> 01:52:02,381
Can you give him the message?

1707
01:52:02,414 --> 01:52:04,414
Certainly.

1708
01:52:05,819 --> 01:52:07,819
This is the message.

1709
01:52:09,154 --> 01:52:11,824
There is no deal for Abel
unless we get Powers and Pryor.

1710
01:52:13,359 --> 01:52:15,828
- Do you understand?
- Yes, Sir.

1711
01:52:15,862 --> 01:52:17,029
It arranged for
tomorrow morning.

1712
01:52:17,162 --> 01:52:19,399
It will not happen,
unless we get two men.

1713
01:52:19,431 --> 01:52:21,134
Those two men.

1714
01:52:21,167 --> 01:52:23,167
- Two, two, two.
- Yes. Sir.

1715
01:52:23,336 --> 01:52:26,206
- Yes.
- If there is no deal.

1716
01:52:26,238 --> 01:52:28,238
Your boss must
tell the Soviets.

1717
01:52:29,408 --> 01:52:31,144
He has to tell the Soviets.

1718
01:52:31,176 --> 01:52:33,212
They are not getting
Rudolf Abel.

1719
01:52:35,414 --> 01:52:37,414
Yes, Sir.

1720
01:52:40,052 --> 01:52:42,052
And, tell him this.

1721
01:52:43,088 --> 01:52:46,059
That so far, Abel has
been a good soldier.

1722
01:52:46,091 --> 01:52:48,161
But he thinks is going home.

1723
01:52:50,363 --> 01:52:52,966
If we have to tell him it,
he is not going home.

1724
01:52:52,998 --> 01:52:54,266
That the Soviets
do not want him.

1725
01:52:54,300 --> 01:52:55,902
That he is never going home.

1726
01:52:55,935 --> 01:52:58,070
I imagine his behavior
might change.

1727
01:53:00,140 --> 01:53:03,009
And who will be held
responsible for that?

1728
01:53:06,880 --> 01:53:08,081
That is a long message.

1729
01:53:08,113 --> 01:53:10,149
Did you get it all?

1730
01:53:10,182 --> 01:53:12,351
- Yes, Sir. I got it.
- Good.

1731
01:53:14,020 --> 01:53:16,020
You are a good man.

1732
01:53:18,123 --> 01:53:19,859
Also, tell him...

1733
01:53:19,893 --> 01:53:21,060
There is no deal,
unless we hear...

1734
01:53:21,094 --> 01:53:22,929
before the end of
business today.

1735
01:53:22,962 --> 01:53:24,229
He has the number.

1736
01:53:24,264 --> 01:53:26,265
If the exchange is
not going to happen.

1737
01:53:26,298 --> 01:53:28,333
No reason for everybody
to get up in the morning.

1738
01:53:28,368 --> 01:53:32,070
No, Sir. That would
be pointless.

1739
01:53:32,104 --> 01:53:34,908
You are kidding me!
You are kidding me!

1740
01:53:34,940 --> 01:53:37,109
Not really.
I need some change.

1741
01:53:37,143 --> 01:53:39,378
This is exactly what you
were not supposed to do.

1742
01:53:39,412 --> 01:53:42,215
My instructions were to
feel out the situation.

1743
01:53:42,247 --> 01:53:45,051
Your instructions were to
get Powers, not Pryor.

1744
01:53:45,083 --> 01:53:47,319
That was not the original
deal. You fouled it up!

1745
01:53:47,353 --> 01:53:49,988
How do you know?
I feel very good about it.

1746
01:53:50,023 --> 01:53:51,390
You fouled it up!

1747
01:53:51,423 --> 01:53:53,225
Do not worry.

1748
01:53:53,259 --> 01:53:55,360
I think it is
going to be fine.

1749
01:53:55,395 --> 01:53:57,395
How do you know?
You do not know that.

1750
01:54:01,266 --> 01:54:03,368
United States. New
York, New York.

1751
01:54:06,005 --> 01:54:08,975
That whole thing...

1752
01:54:09,007 --> 01:54:11,911
Has me to feel out.

1753
01:54:11,944 --> 01:54:14,247
Would I swap one for one?
Which one?

1754
01:54:15,314 --> 01:54:17,283
I said: "No. Two for one."

1755
01:54:17,317 --> 01:54:19,252
They know where we stand.

1756
01:54:19,284 --> 01:54:21,284
Yeah, what if they think
about it and say...

1757
01:54:21,354 --> 01:54:23,488
Forget it! You keep our
person. We keep your people.

1758
01:54:26,426 --> 01:54:28,528
Well, then I have
fucked it all up.

1759
01:54:28,560 --> 01:54:31,064
Hey, honey! It is me.

1760
01:54:31,096 --> 01:54:33,966
Yeah. The fishing
has been great.

1761
01:54:35,969 --> 01:54:37,302
I am in London.

1762
01:54:37,337 --> 01:54:39,377
Just for one more meeting.
Then I am on my way home.

1763
01:54:40,573 --> 01:54:44,042
Yeah, yeah, I remember
that marmalade.

1764
01:54:44,077 --> 01:54:46,179
It is that shop right
by Regent's Park.

1765
01:54:47,479 --> 01:54:49,414
All right! I will
if I have the time.

1766
01:54:49,448 --> 01:54:51,448
Can I say hi to Roger?

1767
01:54:52,452 --> 01:54:54,452
Could I say hi to the girls?

1768
01:54:55,054 --> 01:54:57,054
Is anyone not busy?

1769
01:54:57,422 --> 01:54:59,926
Have they even noticed
I am not around?

1770
01:55:56,215 --> 01:55:58,215
We are on...

1771
01:55:58,451 --> 01:56:00,451
Two for one.

1772
01:56:01,119 --> 01:56:02,088
Hot dog!

1773
01:56:03,122 --> 01:56:05,122
Let us have a drink.

1774
01:56:05,291 --> 01:56:07,291
- One "wrinkle".
- What is that?

1775
01:56:08,060 --> 01:56:10,529
They will not release Pryor
with Powers not on the bridge.

1776
01:56:10,563 --> 01:56:12,297
They will release him
at the same time.

1777
01:56:12,332 --> 01:56:14,434
When the Russians give
us Powers on the bridge.

1778
01:56:14,466 --> 01:56:17,103
They will release Pryor
over Checkpoint Charlie.

1779
01:56:17,136 --> 01:56:18,637
What does that mean?

1780
01:56:18,671 --> 01:56:22,140
I think it means: We want
to have the last word.

1781
01:56:23,176 --> 01:56:25,176
They will do it.

1782
01:56:25,278 --> 01:56:27,278
You tell me.
You felt them out.

1783
01:56:47,567 --> 01:56:49,167
Where are they?

1784
01:56:49,202 --> 01:56:51,025
Where is our person?
Where is our person?

1785
01:56:51,100 --> 01:56:52,171
They are late.

1786
01:56:52,204 --> 01:56:54,140
Nobody is late. We are early.

1787
01:56:54,172 --> 01:56:56,172
- May I?
- Yeah.

1788
01:57:02,582 --> 01:57:03,649
<i>Hoffman?</i>

1789
01:57:03,682 --> 01:57:04,917
<i>Yeah?</i>

1790
01:57:05,251 --> 01:57:06,685
<i>I think they have...</i>

1791
01:57:06,719 --> 01:57:08,453
<i>What?</i>

1792
01:57:08,488 --> 01:57:10,355
Snipers.

1793
01:57:10,390 --> 01:57:12,390
I am sure they have.

1794
01:57:12,557 --> 01:57:14,557
How are you sure they have?

1795
01:57:14,726 --> 01:57:16,726
Because we have snipers.

1796
01:57:34,346 --> 01:57:36,346
Step out, Sir.

1797
01:57:43,756 --> 01:57:45,756
Jim.

1798
01:57:49,429 --> 01:57:51,429
Dear Jim.

1799
01:57:52,465 --> 01:57:54,465
How are you?

1800
01:57:55,234 --> 01:57:57,234
Happy to see you.

1801
01:57:57,436 --> 01:57:59,372
Had you arranged
all this for me?

1802
01:57:59,404 --> 01:58:02,207
Let us see what that is before,
I take credit for it.

1803
01:58:03,509 --> 01:58:05,509
Any word about Pryor
from Checkpoint Charlie?

1804
01:58:29,801 --> 01:58:31,801
Nothing get yet.

1805
01:58:38,243 --> 01:58:39,545
Excuse me, Sir.

1806
01:58:39,578 --> 01:58:41,713
This is Lieutenant Joe Murphy,
the United States Air Force...

1807
01:58:41,747 --> 01:58:43,747
Here to identify Powers.

1808
01:58:44,250 --> 01:58:45,318
Lieutenant Murphy.

1809
01:58:45,751 --> 01:58:47,751
Sir.

1810
01:58:50,422 --> 01:58:52,225
There may be a slight glitch.

1811
01:58:52,257 --> 01:58:54,393
I was a young man when I left.

1812
01:58:54,426 --> 01:58:56,462
Whom will they find
to identify me?

1813
01:58:57,697 --> 01:59:00,432
I hope it is not your
East German family.

1814
01:59:00,466 --> 01:59:02,466
I doubt they could
identify each other.

1815
01:59:37,470 --> 01:59:39,470
Looks like our part.

1816
01:59:46,511 --> 01:59:48,814
Well, let us go.

1817
01:59:48,847 --> 01:59:50,847
You can stay here, Donovan.

1818
01:59:51,650 --> 01:59:53,650
Not likely.

1819
01:59:55,354 --> 01:59:57,354
Open the gate.

1820
02:00:11,570 --> 02:00:13,570
What do you think will
happen, when you get home?

1821
02:00:14,306 --> 02:00:16,306
I think...

1822
02:00:16,641 --> 02:00:18,641
I have vodka.

1823
02:00:21,413 --> 02:00:22,480
Yeah.

1824
02:00:23,381 --> 02:00:24,649
Yeah.

1825
02:00:24,684 --> 02:00:27,485
Rudolf, is there not
the possibility...?

1826
02:00:27,520 --> 02:00:29,588
That my people are
going to shoot me.

1827
02:00:30,789 --> 02:00:32,789
Yes.

1828
02:00:33,626 --> 02:00:35,694
- You are not worried.
- Would it help?

1829
02:00:47,840 --> 02:00:50,810
The answer to your
question, my friend.

1830
02:00:50,842 --> 02:00:53,412
I acted honorably.
I think they know that.

1831
02:00:54,713 --> 02:00:56,582
But sometimes
people think wrong.

1832
02:00:56,615 --> 02:00:58,615
People are people.

1833
02:00:59,551 --> 02:01:01,551
Let us see how they greet me.

1834
02:01:02,755 --> 02:01:04,755
What for can I look?

1835
02:01:07,359 --> 02:01:10,863
If I am embraced or just
shown the back seat.

1836
02:02:05,551 --> 02:02:07,551
<i>Take off the hat.</i>

1837
02:02:13,492 --> 02:02:15,492
Hey, Powers.

1838
02:02:16,494 --> 02:02:18,494
Hey, Murphy.

1839
02:02:19,631 --> 02:02:21,631
Yeah, that is Powers.

1840
02:02:23,703 --> 02:02:25,904
All right! Mr. Donovan.
We go now!

1841
02:02:25,938 --> 02:02:27,938
Hang on!

1842
02:02:34,680 --> 02:02:36,680
Believe me, I will tell you.

1843
02:02:38,050 --> 02:02:40,050
There is no one here.

1844
02:02:42,921 --> 02:02:44,989
They will release another man
at Checkpoint Charlie.

1845
02:02:45,024 --> 02:02:47,025
We are just confirming
that he is there.

1846
02:02:47,059 --> 02:02:48,661
<i>Now!</i>

1847
02:02:48,694 --> 02:02:50,694
As per plan if you, please.

1848
02:02:52,596 --> 02:02:53,032
Let us go.

1849
02:02:53,265 --> 02:02:55,900
Pryor will show up or,
he will not. Let us go.

1850
02:02:55,935 --> 02:02:58,804
They are waiting to see, If
we will do it without him.

1851
02:02:58,837 --> 02:03:01,837
We just have to stand here.
Show them we will not.

1852
02:03:02,541 --> 02:03:03,676
I do not give a shit
what they want.

1853
02:03:03,708 --> 02:03:06,011
We have our objective.
Go ahead, Abel.

1854
02:03:07,813 --> 02:03:10,682
<i>Go ahead, Sir. You can go.</i>

1855
02:03:10,716 --> 02:03:12,784
If it is not the plan,
we go home.

1856
02:03:12,818 --> 02:03:14,818
We exchange now,
or we go home!

1857
02:03:17,555 --> 02:03:19,759
- You are waiting for another man.
- Yes.

1858
02:03:20,826 --> 02:03:22,826
You want him, too.

1859
02:03:24,497 --> 02:03:25,730
I want him.

1860
02:03:25,765 --> 02:03:26,631
Does not matter
what he wants, Sir?

1861
02:03:26,966 --> 02:03:28,966
I am in charge, and
you are free to go.

1862
02:03:29,702 --> 02:03:31,702
Please go. Walk across.

1863
02:03:43,114 --> 02:03:45,114
I can wait.

1864
02:04:09,608 --> 02:04:11,976
It is something.
I am not sure yet.

1865
02:04:14,046 --> 02:04:16,046
Hang on!

1866
02:05:00,059 --> 02:05:02,059
Let us go.

1867
02:05:07,733 --> 02:05:09,733
We got him!

1868
02:05:09,935 --> 02:05:11,935
I...I am...

1869
02:05:13,738 --> 02:05:15,738
I sent you a gift, Jim.

1870
02:05:16,675 --> 02:05:18,675
It is a... It is a painting.

1871
02:05:19,878 --> 02:05:21,913
I hope it has some
meaning to you.

1872
02:05:24,149 --> 02:05:26,649
I am sorry. I did not
think to give you a gift.

1873
02:05:29,889 --> 02:05:31,889
This is your gift.

1874
02:05:35,094 --> 02:05:37,094
This is your gift.

1875
02:06:12,030 --> 02:06:14,030
Are you okay?

1876
02:06:14,867 --> 02:06:16,867
Let us go, let us
go, and let us go!

1877
02:07:35,948 --> 02:07:37,916
Mr. Donovan?

1878
02:07:37,949 --> 02:07:39,949
Colonel Abel asked me
to give this to you.

1879
02:07:42,820 --> 02:07:44,820
Pardon me, Sir.

1880
02:07:45,791 --> 02:07:47,791
Were you in charge
of this thing, sir?

1881
02:07:48,761 --> 02:07:50,895
- Yeah.
- I have to thank you.

1882
02:07:51,796 --> 02:07:53,796
I have to thank somebody.

1883
02:08:10,248 --> 02:08:14,051
I gave them nothing.
I gave them nothing.

1884
02:08:14,252 --> 02:08:16,188
It does not matter.

1885
02:08:16,220 --> 02:08:18,823
It does not matter
what people think.

1886
02:08:18,856 --> 02:08:20,856
You know what you did.

1887
02:09:10,943 --> 02:09:12,943
Welcome home!

1888
02:09:14,345 --> 02:09:16,345
What a trip!

1889
02:09:27,359 --> 02:09:29,359
Are you okay?

1890
02:09:29,394 --> 02:09:31,394
Yeah, I am fine.

1891
02:09:32,997 --> 02:09:35,000
- Did you get the marmalade?
- Yes, yes.

1892
02:09:35,033 --> 02:09:37,069
Yes. Yes.

1893
02:09:37,935 --> 02:09:39,935
I did.

1894
02:09:40,905 --> 02:09:42,905
As ordered.

1895
02:09:46,278 --> 02:09:48,278
Jim?

1896
02:09:48,380 --> 02:09:50,448
- This is from Arno's.
- So?

1897
02:09:50,481 --> 02:09:52,984
- On the corner!
- Well! Honey I was busy.

1898
02:09:53,018 --> 02:09:54,953
- Please. For God's sake.
- We were so busy.

1899
02:09:54,987 --> 02:09:56,387
- How is Roger? Is he home?
- He is home.

1900
02:09:56,421 --> 02:09:58,923
Carol is home, Peggy is home.
Everyone is home.

1901
02:09:58,957 --> 02:10:01,092
<i>Mom? Come quick! Look!</i>

1902
02:10:02,360 --> 02:10:04,395
- Mom comes here!
- Mom comes here!

1903
02:10:04,429 --> 02:10:06,965
- Come see this! Look! Watch!
- Come on!

1904
02:10:06,998 --> 02:10:09,301
<i>Francis Gary Powers.</i>

1905
02:10:09,333 --> 02:10:13,271
<i>Released from prison
in the Soviet Union.</i>

1906
02:10:13,305 --> 02:10:15,373
<i>He turned over to
American authorities.</i>

1907
02:10:15,407 --> 02:10:18,277
<i>Early this morning in Berlin.</i>

1908
02:10:18,310 --> 02:10:23,081
<i>The President commuted
the sentence of Rudolf Abel.</i>

1909
02:10:23,114 --> 02:10:25,984
<i>Mr. Abel has deported.</i>

1910
02:10:26,018 --> 02:10:28,453
<i>He has released in Berlin.</i>

1911
02:10:28,487 --> 02:10:32,090
<i>Efforts to obtain Mr.
Powers released.</i>

1912
02:10:32,123 --> 02:10:34,926
<i>Had underway for some time.</i>

1913
02:10:34,960 --> 02:10:36,461
<i>In recent efforts.</i>

1914
02:10:36,494 --> 02:10:38,497
<i>The United States
government has had...</i>

1915
02:10:38,529 --> 02:10:43,034
<i>The cooperation and assistance
of Mr. James B. Donovan.</i>

1916
02:10:43,068 --> 02:10:45,369
<i>A New York attorney.</i>

1917
02:10:45,404 --> 02:10:49,006
<i>Frederic L. Pryor,
an American student,</i>

1918
02:10:49,041 --> 02:10:51,909
<i>held by East German
authorities,</i>

1919
02:10:51,944 --> 02:10:54,246
<i>since August of 1961.</i>

1920
02:10:54,279 --> 02:10:56,414
I thought Daddy was fishing.

1921
02:10:56,448 --> 02:10:58,448
Salmon.

1922
02:10:58,550 --> 02:11:02,020
<i>Abel now disappeared
into the communist world.</i>

1923
02:11:02,054 --> 02:11:04,288
<i>Powers is answering
questions here.</i>

1924
02:11:04,323 --> 02:11:07,125
<i>And Donovan have gone back
to his practice law.</i>

1925
02:11:07,158 --> 02:11:09,293
<i>Now here is George Finnegan.</i>

1926
02:11:09,328 --> 02:11:12,395
<i>Speaking for the Douglas
Fir Plywood Association.</i>

1927
02:13:28,028 --> 02:13:31,395
<i>Following his return to Russia, Rudolf
Abel was reunited with his wife and daughter.</i>

1928
02:13:31,427 --> 02:13:34,996
<i>He was never publicly acknowledged
by the Soviet Union as a Spy.</i>

1929
02:13:36,427 --> 02:13:38,595
<i>Gary Powers died in a helicopter crash
in 1977, while working for KNBC news.</i>

1930
02:13:38,828 --> 02:13:40,996
<i>He was posthumously awarded
the CIA Director's Medal,</i>

1931
02:13:41,028 --> 02:13:44,996
<i>and the USAF POW Medal in 2000
and the Silver Star in 2012.</i>

1932
02:13:46,127 --> 02:13:48,996
<i>In 1962, Frederic L. Pryor received his
Ph.D. in Economics from Yale University.</i>

1933
02:13:49,127 --> 02:13:51,127
<i>He is currently Professor
Emeritus of Economics,</i>

1934
02:13:51,627 --> 02:13:53,627
<i>and Senior Research Scholar
at Swarthmore College.</i>

1935
02:13:55,018 --> 02:13:57,296
<i>Following the successful conclusion
of the Powers-Abel exchange.</i>

1936
02:13:57,427 --> 02:13:59,296
<i>James Donovan was asked by
President Kenned to undertake,</i>

1937
02:13:59,497 --> 02:14:01,996
<i>further negotiations on
behalf of the U.S.</i>

1938
02:14:03,097 --> 02:14:06,496
<i>In the summer of 1962, he was sent to
Cuba to discuss with Fidel Castro the terms,</i>

1939
02:14:06,997 --> 02:14:08,996
<i>of the release of 1,113 prisoners
held after the Bay of Pigs invasion.</i>

1940
02:14:09,198 --> 02:14:11,996
<i>When Donovan finished negotiations.
He had secured the release,</i>

1941
02:14:12,198 --> 02:14:15,996
<i>of 9,703 men, women
and children.</i>

1942
02:14:17,198 --> 02:14:19,996
"EVERY HUMAN BEING IS IMPORTANT
LIKE FREEDOM"

1943
02:16:04,198 --> 02:16:06,637
BRIDGE OF SPIES
